>>>>> # Know Type 1: Know the signs and symptoms
>>>>> Too many children and young people aren’t diagnosed with Type 1 diabetes
until they are in diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA), a life-threatening condition
>>>>> But by spotting the symptoms of diabetes early and having an immediate
blood glucose finger prick test this can be avoided. The test takes less than
a minute and could save a life. If the result suggests Type 1 diabetes then
the child’s GP should refer them the same day to their local specialist
pediatric team so that they can get the immediate treatment they need to
>>>>> We want to live in a world where diabetes can do no harm. But, we know
that late diagnosis of Type 1 diabetes can be harmful. That’s why we have
launched our Know Type 1 campaign, to raise awareness of the ways that we can
help make sure that children and young people are diagnosed with Type 1
>>>>> ## How will we achieve our mission?
>>>>> The Know Type 1 campaign is aiming to raise awareness of the symptoms of
Type 1 diabetes, how to spot them and how to make sure it is diagnosed
quickly. They are known as the 4 Ts:
>>>>> * Toilet – Going to the toilet a lot, bed wetting by a
previously dry child or heavier nappies in babies.
>>>>> * Thirsty – Being really thirsty and not being able to quench
>>>>> * Tired – Feeling more tired than usual.
>>>>> * Thinner – Losing weight or looking thinner than usual.
>>>>> Type 1 diabetes isn’t currently preventable and nobody knows what causes
it but the signs and symptoms can develop very quickly.
>>>>> We will be raising awareness with the public and healthcare
professionals of the importance of knowing the symptoms of Type 1 diabetes,
knowing what to do if you spot the symptoms and knowing what should happen if
